summary: how dare the show not include bran in the stark montage like they already made us suffer through it after prying dany away and...
question: how dare the show not include bran in the stark montage like they already made us suffer through it after prying dany away and then have the audacity to not add bran like can you believe the little dick energy d&d have?
answer:
Well according to them and also the costume designer whose name I cannot recall rn and pretty much everyone else involved with the show “BrAn Isn’T A sTarK AnYmorE” like yeah sure cool cool cool that makes sense and isn’t ableist or poor writing and filmmaking based on the writers, directors, and producers who were in fact the same 2 people for that episode aren’t interested in Bran as anything more than a plot information machine that is supposed to be omniscient but also conveniently misses tons of info to help throw down certain characters or make others look smart. And he has magical abilities but uses them for… what?

I didn’t watch the episode thank goodness but honestly I wouldn’t be that upset over them excluding him since they’ve destroyed the Stark family, their individual characteristics, their good qualities, and their unification which they sloppily tried to emphasize the last 2 seasons but threw out in this last one. Better to not be a Stark at this point.

summary: Game of Thrones Post-Finale - Revisiting My Season 8 Predictions
title: Game of Thrones Post-Finale - Revisiting My Season 8 Predictions
body:
Game of Thrones Post-Finale – Revisiting My Season 8 Predictions

On the season as a whole, I really don’t have many words. I didn’t go in with high hopes, but this season was a real disappointment, both thematically and as an adaptation – to say nothing of the gamergate-esque regressive views of women, power, and race that it’s vindicated – in direct opposition to what the source material expressly sets out to subvert and deconstruct. Sigh.

Besides that…

summary: The final Game Of Thrones brings a pensive but simple meditation about stories
title: The final Game Of Thrones brings a pensive but simple meditation about stories
excerpt: The epic tale concludes on a somber but simple note, with an episode that meaningfully incorporates the heart and soul of George R.R. Martin's themes of power and belief, and which cleverly uses the show's "a story about stories" tactic to potent effect.
description:
Ultimately, however, that’s also why Bran’s story comes out on top. His isn’t just a tale of extraordinary actions and overcoming adversity. It’s literally the tale of a man who holds their shared history in his mind, who knows more than anyone in the land about just what Westeros and its people have endured through the generations and conflicts that shaped it. Bran isn’t just a great story—he’s literally the repository of all the stories. He’s the living embodiment of the land and its cultural memory. In selecting Bran Stark, the lords of Westeros are choosing to value these stories and memories above whatever other qualities might make a good ruler, and more specifically, put an end to the caprices of heritage that have allowed bloodlines to wreak havoc on good stewardship of these kingdoms.

…  The tragedy is that so much of what happens could have been part of a world with Dany in it. But like a Greek myth, her tragic flaw was her inability to see any future not molded in her image, submissive to her absolute rule. She brought dragons back into this world, and with her death, the last dragons have again departed. She brought fire and death and chaos upon Westeros, yet through her very actions, she may just have made the realm a far better place. […] Game Of Thrones was ultimately about the futility and fraudulence lurking in even the most well-intentioned desire for power, yet it also displayed a surprising sentimentalism for those who could endure the cruelties of life without becoming cruel themselves. It found the potential for a better life in the darkest of places.

summary: I know the show flubbed a lot of characters, but I genuinely think the Biggest Botch Award goes to the way they wrote (or,...
body:
I know the show flubbed a lot of characters, but I genuinely think the Biggest Botch Award goes to the way they wrote (or, rather, didn’t write) Bran. And this is isn’t even going into the books; this is strictly on the show’s own terms.

I mean, think about it. You have titled your show “Game of Thrones.” With this title, you have told us (whether you meant to or not) that the central question of your show is “Who will rule?” Bran is the answer to that question, and you left him out of an entire season.

He WINS THE GAME OF THRONES.

And you decided that for the last two seasons of the show, you would literally take away his personality. One of the most important and powerful characters in the story, and your way of handling this incredible power is to, first, remove him from the story entirely, and then reintroduce him as… not a character at all.

It boggles the mind.
